    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-30T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-30T09:00:00-05:00" n="897"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d897">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.515/568: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-30T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 30, 1943—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 31—12:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>515. From Murphy. Your 477, March 17, 11 p.m. Careful consideration has been
                    given to the question of sending a French expert to Washington to participate in
                    exploratory conversations regarding monetary stabilization in postwar period.
                    The best qualified person whom the French would like to designate is Maurice
                    Couve de Murville.<note n="23" xml:id="d897fn23">Commissioner of Finance, French
                        Committee of National Liberation.</note> Other possibilities are Hervé
                        Alphand<note n="24" xml:id="d897fn24">Director of Economic Affairs, French
                        Committee of National Liberation.</note> and Leroy-Beaulieu,<note n="25"
                        xml:id="d897fn25">French Financial Attaché at Berne.</note> but preference
                    is decidedly in favor of Couve de Murville. However, his functions as Secretary
                    General would not permit his <pb facs="1074" n="1064" xml:id="pg_1064"/>
                    departure at the present time. I feel that unless this question is urgent, a
                    decision should be deferred. What will be the probable date of these
                    discussions? [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
